Esta institución es un proveedor de igualdad de oportunidades.

Parents-
WCES staff is available to help students at arrival. In order to minimize exposure from outside visitors, parents are asked to drop their children off at the outside doors, rather than coming inside the school. Please help us keep the school environment as safe as possible for all students.

Drinking fountains have been shut off to decrease the spread of germs. Please send a filled water bottle to school with your child each day. Bottles may be refilled at the bottle filling stations as needed, but it is helpful if the student begins the day with a full bottle.

Thank you!

post_text:
WCJSHS will follow all KSHSAA guidelines for high school and junior high football and volleyball.

The recommended volleyball guidelines are as follows:

Locker Rooms: Wichita County will provide visiting team locker rooms. Social distancing in the locker room may require changing and showering in groups rather than the entire team.

Pre-Check: We ask that all teams perform temperature checks before leaving their school to ensure bringing safe athletes and personnel into our building.

Crowd: We will have designated areas for team crowds to sit in utilizing the pod system to keep communities separate. We ask that social distancing and masks be worn while in the building. (Games will be suspended until masks are put on). The mask mandate is to ensure we keep all communities safe while they are in our building.

Equipment: Following KSHSAA, we ask that you bring your own volleyballs, we will provide ball carts for warmups.

Concession Stand: There will be no concession stand.

Enrollment is Monday, August 3rd from 7:00 AM-7:00 PM at the Wichita County Junior/Senior High School.

Staff in-service is August 17th & 18th. August 19th is a teacher work day.

K-12 students' first day of school is Thursday, August 20th.

Preschool students' first day of school is Monday, August 24th.

Governor Kelly's Executive Order 20-59 requiring all staff and students to wear masks is in effect, but attorneys are debating whether or not county commissioners have the ability to modify the order. We'll keep you posted as we learn more about this debate.

District staff have been meeting all week to draft a plan for the reopening of school, and when it is completed, we will share it with you.

post_text: In the next few weeks, USD 467 administrators will facilitate the process of developing a plan for reopening schools in August, 2020. The Kansas State Department of Education is planning to release a Navigating Change Document to the public in mid-July. The document will offer guidance to Kansas school districts as they prepare to return to school in the fall. Seeking guidance from KSDE and the Wichita County Health Department, creating stakeholder surveys, and holding meetings to gather information from community members will be part of the planning process, Please be assured that USD 467 is considering the safety of students, staff, and the community as the reopening plan is developed. Thank you for your patience during this unprecedented time.

post_text: USD 467 congratulates Mr. Keith Higgins on retiring after 43 years in education. During the course of his school career, Mr. Higgins has taught Vocal Music, coached multiple sports, drove an activity bus, worked in food service, custodial, served as Principal, and Superintendent, and numerous other positions. We can't thank him enough for the 12 years he has spent at Wichita County and the countless students and staff members he has served. Thank you Mr. Higgins and enjoy your retirement!

post_text:
We would like to thank everyone that is participating in the breakfast/lunch program offered daily. We have been asked if it would be possible to do one day pick up for breakfasts and lunches for five days worth of food. We are currently making on average 250 breakfasts and 250 lunches per day. The size of our kitchen and refrigeration unit would not hold 2,500 sacked breakfasts/lunches at once. We currently are only able to handle the amount made daily. Every day is a learning experience and we are striving to improve our meal service. Thank you for all of the community feedback, we greatly appreciate it.
USD #467 Food Service Director

Deb Chidester found some some free resources for kids and parents to use to get books and audio-books.

https://nothingintherulebook.com/2017/01/10/55-places-you-can-download-tens-of-thousands-books-plays-and-other-literary-texts-completely-legally-for-free/

https://stories.audible.com/start-listen?mi_cmp=98ba55cbab885926&mi_ecmp=486894200&mi_sc=t&mi_u=amzn1.account.AHO5G4BOQURXRPIGW4XE4HZIPSPQ

If you have an Amazon prime account there are books on there that you can read for free. You need a Kindle app.

http://www.gutenberg.org/

https://librivox.org/

https://www.baen.com/allbooks/category/index/id/2012 mainly science fiction.

https://archive.org/ also has movies, software, music, websites, and more.

You can also search for a title as a PDF file to see if it is online to read. Usually not new titles.

post_text: Effective Monday, March 16, all spring sports and activities are suspended through Sunday, March 22. This includes cancellation of all practices and competitions for this week. This prohibition is consistent with KSDE and governmental guidance and may be extended, should conditions warrant. Please note spring sports team members are prohibited from club or outside team participation and practice during this period. Not only would such outside participation be contrary to handbook rule, it would be contrary to the very reason activities are cancelled during the time we seek to mitigate potential transfer of the contagion.

Kansas Farm Bureau
February 19 at 9:12 AM ·

Each year, Kansas Farm Bureau provides scholarships to students pursuing education after high school. Currently, KFB has scholarships for students attending Kansas State University, Fort Hays State University, technical schools and students who are members of a Collegiate Farm Bureau chapter.

The application deadline is March 1 for all scholarships. Learn more at https://www.kfb.org/Foundation-for-Agriculture/Scholarships.

We send a HUGE thank you to the Knights for continuing to help us make a safe and "warm" place for our students! Their smiles tell it all!

post_text: Although it doesn’t seem like it, there is progress being made on the WCES roof. The School Board approved the proposed roofing project at the April 22nd meeting earlier this year. Unfortunately the roofers delayed starting the project until just recently. They have been working longer hours and though the weekends and we hope they finish soon. The peaked, shingled roof on the building is nearly complete and they have been preparing the flat roof sections. We know that the students and staff are getting tired of all the noise and tar smell. Thank you for your patience!
text: Although it doesn’t seem like it, there is progress being made on the WCES roof. The School Board approved the proposed roofing project at the April 22nd meeting earlier this year. Unfortunately the roofers delayed starting the project until just recently. They have been working longer hours and though the weekends and we hope they finish soon. The peaked, shingled roof on the building is nearly complete and they have been preparing the flat roof sections. We know that the students and staff are getting tired of all the noise and tar smell. Thank you for your patience!
